INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('1', 'Kaunas Central Post Office Palace (now – National Institute of Architecture)', '1930, architect Feliksas Vizbaras | 102 Laisvės Ave.', 'Laisvės al. 102', '<p>In 1929, it was decided to construct a new Central Post Office – envisaged as both the epicentre and emblem of a modern communications system. In the same year, the Ministry of Transport and Communications of Lithuania announced a design competition for the palace, which was won by the architect F. Vizbaras.</p><p>The design was conceived as an innovative interpretation of Lithuanian vernacular architecture, drawing on the spatial logic of a traditional village dwelling, incorporating motifs of folk weaving in the frieze and floor decoration, and articulating a modern national style within the transaction hall.</p><p>Within less than a year, a five-storey structure featuring a pronounced symmetrical façade and a flat roof was erected. The building became one of the most prominent architectural landmarks of the provisional capital. Construction work was executed exclusively by local craftsmen, while the interior was enriched with works by leading artists of the period: the upper section of the operations hall was decorated with the coats of arms of Vilnius, Grodno, and Klaipėda, alongside three paintings by Kazys Šimonis. Encircling the hall were 103 Lithuanian postage stamps painted by the artists Petras and Rimtas Kalpokas.</p><p>Following the occupation of Lithuania, Soviet authorities sought to diminish the symbolic significance of the building: commemorative plaques bearing the names of sponsors and project initiators were concealed beneath plaster, and a commemorative medallion was removed from the façade. After the restoration of Lithuania’s independence, efforts were made to restore the interior details. In 2024, the National Institute of Architecture commenced its activities in the building.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/1.jpg', '54.89814140', '23.90447380');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('2', 'Vytautas the Great War Museum and the M. K. Čiurlionis National Museum of Art', '1921–1936, architects Vladimiras Dubeneckis, Karolis Reisonas | 64 K. Donelaičio St. / 55 V. Putvinskio St.', 'K. Donelaičio g. 64 / V. Putvinskio g. 55', '<p>The concept of a National Museum emerged in the early 20th century, driven by a rising tide of national consciousness. It subsequently evolved into a vision of an institution that would function not only as a monument to statehood and a repository of collective memory, but also as a centre for the education and cultivation of a modern society.</p><p>The formation of the complex began in 1921 with the establishment of an exhibition dedicated to the Lithuanian Wars of Independence in a former wooden riding hall, accompanied by the erection of the first monument in the museum garden – To Those Who Died for the Freedom of Lithuania. The stones for the monument were collected and brought from sites of the independence struggles; later, in 1934, the Unknown Soldier was solemnly buried here.</p><p>In 1929 and 1930, two architectural competitions were organised with the objective of accommodating two museums – dedicated respectively to war history and culture – within a single building. The winning designs were produced by two of the most prominent architects of interwar Lithuania, V. Dubeneckis and K. Reisonas. In 1930, the foundation stone was consecrated, and the building was formally named in honour of Vytautas the Great. The architectural composition of the monumental complex aspires to symmetry, although the façades exhibit distinct formal treatments.</p><p>The arcaded galleries of the War Museum extend the main volume, linking it to the bell tower, whose decorative programme is thematically integrated with the museum interiors and the surrounding memorials. In contrast, the façade of the Museum of Culture is more dynamic in expression. Its principal compositional motif draws on imagery found in the paintings of M. K. Čiurlionis: a semi-circular central section articulated by narrow vertical windows and intermediate pilasters crowned with copper caps.</p><p>The interior is characteristic of representative public architecture, dominated by a restrained palette of white, grey, black, and dark wood, which creates a dignified and subdued setting for the exhibits.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/2.jpg', '54.89988250', '23.91186280');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('3', 'The Representative Palace of the Lithuanian Officers Club (Ramovė)', '1931–1937, architect Stasys Kudokas| 19 A. Mickevičiaus St.', 'A. Mickevičiaus g. 19', '<p>Military strength was regarded as one of the principal guarantors of sovereignty in interwar Lithuania, and the officer corps sought to reinforce this perception, as well as public confidence, through active participation in the political, social, and cultural life of the state. Accordingly, it was resolved to establish a representative architectural space capable of embodying the grandeur of Lithuanian history.</p><p>The international competition announced in 1931 attracted proposals from approximately thirty architects and design teams. Although the competition was won by the Estonian architects E. Lohkas and H. Voldemaras Johansonas, the project was implemented by Lithuanian architects. Officially opened on 23 April 1937, the Officers’ Club rapidly became one of the most opulent buildings in interwar Kaunas and a focal point of urban social life: a venue for officers’ assemblies, state ceremonies, receptions, and conferences.</p><p>The building is distinguished by a synthesis of classicism and modernism: the ground floor is articulated with granite columns and half-columns, the façade is crowned by a pronounced cornice and an attic concealing the roof, while the windows of the piano nobile are emphatically accentuated. The historicist interior spaces are juxtaposed with a modern steel-framed glazed conservatory.</p><p>Above the principal entrance, Lithuanian territorial integrity is symbolically expressed through Bronius Pundzius’s granite reliefs depicting the coats of arms of Vilnius, Kaunas, and Klaipėda, as well as the sculpture of the Three Giants positioned along the cornice.</p><p>The building follows a tripartite palatial scheme: a public ground floor comprising vestibules and cloakrooms, a restaurant, and symmetrically arranged staircases leading to the representative floor with thematic halls (the Vytautas the Great Hall, the President’s Room, and the Dukes’ Hall) and leisure areas; and an upper “residential” level with open balcony loggias and accommodation for temporary stays.</p>', '../../ehl-pastatai69e87713b6092.jpg', '54.89666570', '23.91645900');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('4', 'The State Savings Bank (now – Kaunas City Municipal Administration)', '1938–1940, architects Arnas Funkas, Adolfas Lukošatis, Bronius Elsbergas | 96 Laisvės Ave.', 'Laisvės al. 96', '<p>One of the final major public buildings realised during the interwar period was the State Savings Bank. The project was conceived as a prestigious undertaking, incorporating advanced technologies and contemporary design principles. A specially appointed commission undertook study visits to analogous buildings across Europe.</p><p>An international architectural competition for the building was announced in 1938, attracting approximately seventy-seven proposals; the final design was synthesised from three projects selected by the jury.</p><p>The six-storey structure was colloquially referred to by residents as the Kaunas Skyscraper, reflecting its intended multifunctional use: in addition to the savings bank, it housed the Department of Trade, the Bureau of Statistics, and other state institutions. While the installation of two lifts no longer constituted a novelty, the inclusion of a pneumatic post system represented a modern technological feature, facilitating rapid internal communication between floors. A secure vault in the basement ensured the safeguarding of deposits.</p><p>The building comprises three interconnected volumes of five and six storeys, arranged around a semi-enclosed courtyard. Its architectural expression is defined by rigorous geometric forms and a restrained, rational compositional logic. Revolving doors mark the principal entrance.</p><p>The ground floor is clad in polished granite slabs, while the upper storeys are finished in grey granite render. The structural system is based on a metal frame, and the roofs are predominantly flat, with the exception of the main hall, which features a distinctive Art Deco ceiling composed of a black metal framework forming a geometric pattern.</p><p>National decorative motifs are subtly integrated into the finishes, including stylised tulips, rue branches, solar symbols, and arrows, interpreted through a modernist idiom.</p><p>Following the Second World War, the building housed the Kaunas Executive Committee and the Communist Party Committee until 1990. Following the restoration of Lithuania&#x27;s independence, the building became the seat of the Kaunas City Municipality, which was defended during the events of January 1991.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/4.jpg', '54.89827810', '23.90645950');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('5', 'Kaunas District Municipality Palace (now – Kaunas District Police Commissariat)', '1933, architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis | 91 Vytauto Ave.', 'Vytauto pr. 91', '<p>The modern building played a decisive role in shaping the urban image of the new capital. Erected in 1933, the palace accommodated two institutions within a single structure: the wing facing Laisvės Avenue housed the offices of the Kaunas District Municipality and the Police Commissariat, while the wing along Vytauto Avenue was allocated to the State Security Department and the Criminal Police, with detention facilities installed in the basement.</p><p>A two-storey garage, incorporating residential units for drivers and a printing facility, was constructed within the courtyard. Technical supervision of the construction works was carried out by engineers Algirdas Šalkauskas and Borisas Helcermanas.</p><p>The geometrically rigorous architectural language, narrow window openings, and articulated pilasters conveyed a representative character consistent with other interwar public buildings in Kaunas. The building distinguished itself within its urban context not only through its modernist geometric forms but also through its material opulence. Interior finishes and engineering solutions further emphasised the institutional status and financial capacity of the occupying bodies. The plinth and staircases executed in natural dark grey granite, portals clad in polished black labradorite, and pilasters of dark artificial granite created a pronounced contrast with the light granite façades.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/5.jpg', '54.89721990', '23.92493870');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('6', 'Chamber of Commerce, Industry, and Crafts (now – departments of the Kaunas Ąžuolynas Library)', '1938, architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis | 8 K. Donelaičio St.', 'K. Donelaičio g. 8', '<p>Lithuanian intellectual and professional circles broadly agreed that economic strength constituted a fundamental guarantee of statehood. One of the principal symbols of the expanding national economy and commercial sector became the Chamber of Commerce and Industry – an institution established in 1925 to coordinate and represent the interests of industrialists and merchants. Its symbolic role was to underscore the premise that a robust economy forms the foundation of national prosperity.</p><p>In 1931, a decision was taken to construct a modern representative headquarters building. The project attracted considerable attention, with as many as twenty-nine proposals submitted; ultimately, the commission was awarded to architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis, who advocated a synthesis of classical tradition and national stylistic principles. The architectural concept was intended to embody territorial integrity, demographic potential, social cohesion, national values, and the sustained development of industry, commerce, agriculture, and crafts.</p><p>Initially, the site was envisaged adjacent to the War Museum bell tower; however, it was later decided to reinforce the urban composition of K. Donelaičio Street as anartery of the New Town. Two adjacent plots were acquired for this purpose.</p><p>The completed building exemplifies the restraint, solidity, and integration of architecture with applied arts characteristic of Lithuanian interwar architecture. The principal three-storey volume is aligned along K. Donelaičio Street, with the façade vertically articulated by pilaster strips and an arched entrance portal. The side elevation is more neutral in character, structured by three continuous horizontal bands of windows.</p><p>The entrances are accentuated by emblematic reliefs entitled Industry and Trade. Five mural compositions by P. Kalpokas adorn the vestibule, while stained-glass works by Stasys Ušinskas – Lithuanian Boy and Lithuanian Girl – enrich the staircase. An additional symbolic accent is provided by metal vases designed by B. Pundzius, decorated with relief representations of industrial motifs.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/6.jpg', '54.89835870', '23.92491800');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('7', 'Žaliakalnis Funicular', '1931, the initial project was prepared by Curt Rudolph Transportanlagen; subsequent works in 1937 were designed by engineer Napoleonas Daukas-Dobkevičius | 6 Aušros St.', 'Aušros g. 6', '<p>During the interwar period, urban modernity was closely associated with infrastructural development. Historic funicular systems constitute one of the most salient indicators of Kaunas’s urban growth. In 1927, the municipal authorities approved the installation of a funicular to stimulate and accelerate the development of the Žaliakalnis district.</p><p>The construction initiative was formally launched in 1931 in Žaliakalnis by President Antanas Smetona and City Burgomaster Jonas Vileišis. The project arose from the need to improve connectivity between the New Town and Žaliakalnis. As the city expanded, it was observed that development in the upper districts declined, while construction intensified in the lower areas, where land values increased significantly. This disparity was attributed to the limited accessibility between different parts of the city.</p><p>Following the decision to construct the funicular, extensive deliberations were undertaken to determine the most suitable location, including the application of early sociological survey methods. To assess potential passenger flows, the municipality employed individuals to monitor pedestrian movement along existing routes.</p><p>The findings indicated that the highest volume of movement occurred along Kauko Street (approximately 4,000 persons per day), followed by Žemaičių Street (3,500), and Aušros Path (3,000). On the basis of these data, it was decided to locate the installation at Putvinskio Street (then Kalnų Street), near house No. 22, extending to the intersection of Aušros and Žemaičių Streets.</p><p>Initially, the system operated with a single passenger carriage, while a second carriage loaded with stones functioned as a counterweight. With the rapid increase in popularity, a second passenger carriage was soon introduced. Additional infrastructure improvements included the installation of a shelter at the lower station, followed later by a canopy that has remained unchanged to the present day.</p><p>Beyond its utilitarian function, the funicular also became a notable urban attraction. During the interwar period, it is estimated that the system operated more than 200 trips per working day, transporting on average over 3,000 passengers, with each carriage accommodating up to 35 individuals. The track extended over a length of 142 metres, and the journey duration was approximately 1 minute 38 seconds.</p><p>The system was designed and manufactured by the Leipzig-based engineering firm Curt Rudolph Transportanlagen, while the electrical equipment was supplied by the AEG corporation. The funicular carriages were produced in Kaunas by the Lithuanian-American trading company Amlit.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/7.jpg', '54.90199690', '23.91789750');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('8', 'Pažanga Company Palace', '1934, architect Feliksas Vizbaras | 53 Laisvės Ave.', 'Laisvės al. 53', '<p>The Pažanga company, established in 1928, was affiliated with the ruling Nationalist Party, formerly known as the National Progress Party. The name of both the company and the palace derives directly from this political association.</p><p>The five-storey building, constructed between 1933 and 1934, accommodated the party headquarters, the editorial offices of Lietuvos aidas and Jaunoji karta, as well as the National Youth Union Jaunoji Lietuva. A National Club, incorporating a café and restaurant, was located on the second floor. Visitors had access to a flat-roof terrace via an elevator.</p><p>The ground floor housed a haberdashery operated by the Parama company and a bookstore run by the Dirva company. In 1934, the State Central Bookstore and Library were also relocated to the premises. Beneath the courtyard, an extensive basement level accommodated meeting rooms and a reading hall, illuminated by skylights constructed from glass blocks.</p><p>In pursuit of a modern national architectural language, architect F. Vizbaras employed Art Deco motifs in both the façade and interior design, incorporating geometric patterns, zigzags, and floral elements.</p><p>Separate entrances were provided on either side of the ground floor: the western entrance led to the representative areas, while the eastern entrance provided access to the courtyard wings. For a period, Prime Minister Juozas Tūbelis resided above the editorial offices of Lietuvos aidas; in 1935, an apartment in the palace was occupied by the politician, former Prime Minister, co-founder of the Pažanga company, and signatory of the Act of Independence, Reverend Vladas Mironas. After 1940, the building accommodated various research institutions, while residential units were established in the courtyard wings and commercial premises operated along Laisvės Avenue.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/8.jpg', '54.89709910', '23.91421650');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('9', 'Vytautas the Great University Faculty of Medicine Building', '1933, architect Vladimiras Dubeneckis | 9 A. Mickevičiaus St.', 'A. Mickevičiaus g. 9', '<p>The Faculty of Medicine building in Kaunas represents an example of early 20th-century Neoclassical architecture, reflecting a transitional phase between Retrospectivism and Modernism. The symmetrical and monumental composition negotiates a balance between modernist tendencies and classical tradition.</p><p>The building was designed in 1930, drawing upon a project for the Faculty of Medicine at the University of Brussels, adapted to Lithuania’s economic conditions and consequently simplified in form and programme. The foundation stone was consecrated in July 1931, and construction was completed in less than two years.</p><p>V. Dubeneckis&#x27; building is functionally organised into administrative offices and teaching facilities, a connecting wing with lecture rooms, and a dedicated research block. The newly constructed palace significantly improved the working and learning conditions of medical students and academic staff, aligning them more closely with contemporary European standards.</p><p>Prior to that, macabre reports appeared in the press: “until the faculty acquired a properly equipped anatomical theatre, the renowned surgeon and professor of anatomy Jurgis Žilinskas had converted his private apartment into a makeshift morgue” (Lietuvos aidas, 04 July 1931, No. 147), “while improvised wooden crates were assembled to hold cadavers and benches procured for students” (J. Žilinskas, Memoirs, Vilnius: Lithuanian National Museum, 2005, p. 192.)</p><p>The façades of the building are characterised by symmetry and monumentality, incorporating elements associated with historicist architecture, most prominently expressed on the A. Mickevičiaus Street elevation. Here, the central section, flanked by avant-corps and emphasised by a formal entrance, together with a stepped parapet and a high Classicist portal, evokes the compositional language of a traditional palace. By contrast, the Spaustuvininkų Street façade adopts a markedly more modern expression, featuring curved forms and extensive glazing.</p><p>Within a single institutional complex were established the institutes of anatomy, forensic and social medicine, and general pathology with pathological anatomy, as well as the Anatomy Museum, which continues to operate to this day. The wing along A. Mickevičiaus Street accommodated facilities for physiology and physiological chemistry, pharmacology, histology with embryology, and pharmacy with pharmacognosy. In 1936, the first crematorium in Lithuania was installed in the basement of the building.</p><p>The Faculty of Medicine also occupies a notable place in national historical memory: in 1933, following their tragic deaths, the transatlantic aviators Steponas Darius and Stasys Girėnas were recognised as national heroes, and a decision was taken to embalm their remains. With the approach of the Soviet army and the onset of renewed occupation, the pilots’ remains were concealed in the basement of the Faculty of Medicine until 1963.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/9.jpg', '54.89430490', '23.91635660');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('10', 'Kaunas Land Bank Building (now – KTU Central Building)', '1935, architect Karolis Reisonas | 73 K. Donelaičio St.', 'K. Donelaičio g. 73', '<p>In 1924, the Land Bank – the largest agricultural credit institution in Lithuania – was established by state initiative to provide loans to farmers. The building was constructed on the edge of Unity Square; accordingly, architect K. Reisonas sought to ensure that the structure would not visually dominate the adjacent museum complex.</p><p>The four-storey building presents a monumental composition, articulated by a rhythm of vertical and horizontal elements across its façades, and enriched by high-quality finishing materials, including granite render, polished granite cladding, and integrated works of art. A high parapet conceals the pitched roof, which is further enlivened by stylised rosettes, while the avant-corps are adorned with bas-reliefs by sculptor Bernardas Bučas depicting peasant heads. The construction made extensive use of reinforced concrete. The principal architectural accent is the corner entrance, emphasised by broad granite staircases.</p><p>The building comprises three volumes of varying scale, accommodating banking halls, cashier facilities, and a secure vault. It also housed offices of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, accessible via separate entrance and lift. The final foreign ministers of independent Lithuania – S. Lozoraitis (1934–1938) and J. Urbšys (1938–1940) – worked in this building.</p><p>By 1935, as functionalist principles gained increasing prominence, the interior design prioritised spacious, well-lit, and hygienic environments: “there are no expensive installations, various plaster embellishments, or ornaments in the newly built Land Bank building; although they decorate the interior, they always encourage the accumulation of dust” (Lietuvos aidas, 12 February 1935).</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/10.jpg', '54.89880520', '23.91265260');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('11', 'Pienocentras Company Office', '1934, architects Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis, Karolis Reisonas | 55 Laisvės Ave.', 'Laisvės al. 55', '<p>The Lithuanian Union of Dairy Cooperatives, Pienocentras, was established in 1927. It rapidly developed into one of the largest industrial enterprises in Lithuania, overseeing the collection, processing, distribution, and export of dairy products.</p><p>In 1931, architect V. Landsbergis-Žemkalnis won the competition for the design of the Pienocentras administrative building, with K. Reisonas also contributing to the project. Structural calculations were carried out by engineers J. Milius and P. Markūnas. Construction, completed in 1934, was executed under the supervision of contractors L. Markovičius and J. Kaplanas.</p><p>The five-storey building on Laisvės Avenue appeared as a skyscraper in comparison to its lower-rise surroundings. It represents one of the most significant examples of a multifunctional (commercial and residential) building in interwar Kaunas.</p><p>The ground floor accommodated a branded Pienocentras retail store and a milk bar, which quickly became a popular urban destination. A nearby snack bar, known as the Pienocentras Garden, further expanded its public function. The renowned Muralis Brothers hairdressing salon, featuring modernist interiors designed by architect Arnas Funkas, occupied the lower two floors. Administrative offices were located on the third floor, while the upper levels were designated for residential use. Prior to the establishment of a central dairy facility in Kaunas, a small dairy and refrigeration unit operated in the buildings’ basement.</p><p>The structure can be regarded as a key example of Lithuanian functionalism, characterised by restrained symmetry and a profiled cornice reflecting elements of modernised historicism. The curved main façade, with large display windows and an electrically illuminated canopy, reflects influences of European Expressionism. Curved corner windows, preserved on the second floor, further contributed to the buildings’ modern character and visual refinement.</p><p>Together with the adjacent Pažanga Palace, the building contributed to the formation of the emerging urban core of a modern European capitals’ principal boulevard. In 1937, at the Exposition Internationale des Arts et des Techniques in Paris, the building was awarded an honorary diploma and a bronze medal.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/11.jpg', '54.89709830', '23.91386320');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('13', 'Physical Culture Academy Building (now – Lithuanian Sports University)', '1934, architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis | 6 Sporto St.', 'Sporto g. 6', '<p>In Lithuania, following the restoration of independence after the First World War, agriculture was prioritised, while sport was often regarded as a secondary or leisure activity. This perception shifted fundamentally in 1932 with the adoption of the Law on Physical Culture. Sport was thereafter institutionalised as a field actively promoted by the state rather than the domain of individual societies. Lithuanian émigrés played a significant role in this transformation, disseminating ideas of physical culture and training local communities.</p><p>One of the most prominent figures was the aviator Steponas Darius, who popularised ten different sports within a period of seven months and initiated the construction of the first stadium in Kaunas. Another key contributor to the development of sport in Lithuania was Steponas Garbačiauskas. On his initiative, the first tennis court was established in Vytautas Park. These examples illustrate a broader movement that reshaped attitudes towards physical culture.</p><p>The first state institution dedicated to sport commenced its activities in Kaunas in 1932. However, the initial phase of construction of the Physical Culture Palace was completed only in 1934. The building was originally planned for Kęstučio Street, but the Ąžuolynas area was ultimately selected as a more appropriate location, combining proximity to the city centre with a distance from its noise and pollution. The structure was erected adjacent to Lithuania’s first stadium, established in 1925, and the former Tennis Club grounds.</p><p>The dominant component of the cross-shaped plan is the main hall, covered by a glazed vaulted reinforced concrete ceiling that imparts a sense of lightness and spatial elegance. At the time of construction, such a structural solution was considered highly innovative.</p><p>Two smaller gymnasiums were attached as lateral annexes. Administrative offices and classrooms were arranged in the central part of the building. These facilities were intended for the training of physical education teachers and military instructors, as well as for organising sports-related events and lectures.</p><p>The symmetrical volumetric composition reflects the principles of Italian Rationalism. The architectural concept is succinctly expressed in the words of architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis: “In designing this building, we sought to combine two forms within a single structure: to connect the classical tradition, represented by ancient Greece as the cradle of physical culture, with the demands of modernity. The halls were therefore conceived in a classical spirit, with only essential elements adapted to contemporary architectural requirements. At the same time, the intention was to achieve a fully modern architectural expression”.</p><p>The original design envisaged the building’s primary feature as Lithuania’s first modern indoor swimming pool. Until that time, athletes had been limited to training in open water bodies. The proposed pool was conceived as an advanced facility, incorporating underwater lighting and a retractable glass roof that would allow sunlight and fresh air to enter during the summer months. However, due to economic constraints and subsequent revisions to the project, this feature was realised only in 1959, approximately twenty-five years after its initial conception.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/13.jpg', '54.89834740', '23.93457550');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('14', 'Sports Hall of the Kaunas Ąžuolynas Sports Facilities Complex', '1939, engineer Anatolijus Rozenbliumas | 5 Perkūno Ave.', 'Perkūno al. 5', '<p>The Sports Hall represents the first purpose-built basketball arena in Europe. The decision to construct the facility was taken in 1937, following the victory of the Lithuanian national team at the European Basketball Championship in Riga. It was subsequently announced that the 1939 European Basketball Championship would be hosted in Kaunas.</p><p>Constructed within an exceptionally short period of six months, the Sports Hall brought international recognition both to Lithuanian sport and to its principal engineer, Anatolijus Rozenbliumas.</p><p>The technically complex construction process was undertaken under significant time constraints and was further complicated by the fact that most of the work was carried out during winter conditions. In some instances, foundations were cast at temperatures as low as –20 °C, requiring the use of specialised heating equipment.</p><p>To maximise the interior span, a vaulted structural system was adopted, consisting of four riveted arches supported by reinforced concrete foundations. Triangular skylights integrated into the roof structure between the arches provided abundant natural daylight.</p><p>In May 1939, the 13,000-seat arena was inaugurated, and the first training sessions commenced. The basketball court was regarded as the finest in Europe at the time. However, the austere and highly utilitarian exterior of the building was not universally appreciated, as contemporaries perceived a lack of decorative elements.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/14.jpg', '54.89743330', '23.93733320');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('15', 'Romuva Cinema', '1940, architect Nikolajus Mačiulskis| Laisvės Ave. 54', 'Laisvės al. 54', '<p>During the interwar period, Laisvės Avenue – the principal thoroughfare of Kaunas – became known as the “cinema boulevard” due to the presence of twelve cinemas. This popularity reflected the accessibility of cinema to a broad spectrum of society, offering an escape from everyday life and exposure to diverse cultures and imagery.</p><p>Opened on 18 April 1940, Romuva was recognised as the largest and most modern cinema in Kaunas, surpassing not only other venues in Lithuania but also several in the Baltic region in terms of originality.</p><p>The history of the building began in 1938, when entrepreneurs Antanas and Petras Steikūnas acquired a plot on Laisvės Avenue. Construction of the Art Deco “little castle” commenced the following year, based on a design by architect Nikolajus Mačiulskis. Within a single year, the building was erected at the rear of the plot, thereby creating a cohesive and intimate public space at the cinemas’ entrance.</p><p>The defining feature of Romuva is its Art Deco façade, marked by a tall, illuminated glass tower rising above the entrance canopy. Advertising was intended to be displayed in an innovative manner against a background of changing coloured illumination; however, due to the outbreak of war, the equipment designated for this purpose failed to reach its destination. The façade composition is articulated into several horizontal tiers by profiled surrounds framing rows of windows of varying dimensions.</p><p>The 687-seat auditorium was equipped in accordance with the most advanced cinematographic standards of the time, including a powerful mechanical ventilation system and Zeis-Kono projection equipment. The oval-shaped hall, specialised wall finishes, and inclined reinforced concrete ribbed vaults were designed by engineer Pranas Markūnas, a pioneer of reinforced concrete structures in Lithuania. These design solutions were intended to optimise acoustic performance.</p><p>The circular geometry of the auditorium is echoed throughout the building in the vestibule, corridors, staircase, and entrance porch. Such design strategies reflect the influence of the Streamline Moderne aesthetic prevalent in the United States, while also incorporating elements of a national stylistic vocabulary. Another distinctive feature of the interior is the pervasive use of rhombic motifs across ceilings, floors, windows, and doors.</p><p>Today, Romuva remains the oldest continuously operating cinema in Lithuania, having preserved both its primary function and external appearance. The building underwent renovation in 2020, during which the façade, windows, doors, and other authentic Art Deco interior elements were carefully restored. A spacious stage, suitable for dance, theatre, musical performances, and conferences, was installed in the main hall.</p>', '../../ehl-pastatai69e876cb10bb3.jpg', '54.89775930', '23.91566350');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('16', 'Church of the Resurrection of Christ', '1933–2004, architect Karolis Reisonas | 31A Žemaičių St.', 'Žemaičių g. 31A', '<p>For many decades, the interwar architecture of Kaunas functioned as a powerful expression of national identity. This is exemplified by the dominant feature of the Kaunas skyline – the Church of the Resurrection – which has endured numerous historical transformations.</p><p>The concept of constructing a memorial church in Kaunas, symbolising the rebirth of the Lithuanian nation and expressing gratitude to God, emerged in 1922. The initiative was rooted in the tradition of votive offerings in Christian culture, which developed as a form of popular piety and church-building practice, first observed in Austria and France in the late 19th century and becoming more widespread in the 20th century.</p><p>An architectural competition for the Church of the Resurrection was announced in 1928, stipulating three principal requirements: a monumental form, the inclusion of a national mausoleum, and the expression of a distinct Lithuanian identity. Fifteen proposals were submitted, and the competition was won by architect Karolis Reisonas. Žaliakalnis Hill was selected as the site in order to ensure the buildings’ visibility within the urban panorama of Kaunas.</p><p>Construction commenced in 1933 with the laying of the foundations, although financial challenges soon emerged; the transportation of the cornerstone from the Mount of Olives in Jerusalem proved particularly costly, prompting intensified fundraising efforts. During these campaigns, symbolic donation “bricks” valued at 10 and 50 cents and 1 LTL were distributed to contributors. This initiative enabled broad public participation, allowing residents to support the project according to their means. As a result, nearly half of the required funds were raised through public donations.
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('17', 'Former Residential House of Beras Goldbergas (now privately owned)', '1937, architect Volfas Brūnas | 52 V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio g. 52', '<p>In 1936, the Kaunas-based Litvak Beras (Boris) Goldbergas acquired a plot on the prestigious Kalnų Street (now V. Putvinskio Street) and initiated the construction of a six-apartment residential building. All construction works were supervised by technician and engineer Volfas Brūnas.</p><p>The original design underwent several revisions, including requirements to harmonise the façade with neighbouring buildings: the heights of the cornice, plinth, and windows were to be aligned, and side windows unified within a common framing system. During construction, deviations from the approved design occurred: a small window was introduced above the street entrance to illuminate the staircase, decorative niches above the windows were omitted, and additional openings were created in the plinth.</p><p>Completed within a single year, the building became a notable example of modern construction and Modernist architecture, frequently featured in contemporary periodicals and included in the list of prize-eligible buildings in 1937.</p><p>The façade is characterised by a restrained, symmetrical, and proportionally balanced composition typical of International Modernism, defined by a white colour palette, clean lines, wide window openings, and minimalist French-style balconies with metal railings. The entrance is accentuated by a window screened with horizontal concrete elements. Subtle references to Historicism are also present in the architectural language of the building. Each floor contains two compact three-room apartments.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/17.jpg', '54.90084490', '23.91280630');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('18', 'Former House of Physician Nadiežda Nagornienė (now privately owned)', '1934, Adolfas Netyksa | 54 V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio g. 54', '<p>In 1933, physician Nadiežda Nagornienė submitted an application to the municipal authorities for the construction of a three-storey residential building on present-day V. Putvinskio Street. The design brief required that each floor accommodate apartments suitable for professionals engaged in private practice, such as doctors and lawyers, with separate access from the staircase to offices and waiting rooms, as well as service entrances to the kitchens.</p><p>The project was entrusted to architect Adolfas Netyksa, who designed a compact modernist apartment building integrated within the existing urban block. From the commencement of construction to its completion, the project underwent three revisions. Due to multiple regulatory violations, construction was halted on several occasions, and a number of legal proceedings were initiated in response to unauthorised alterations and non-compliance with the approved design. Even after completion, legal disputes concerning the building persisted for a further two years.</p><p>The three-storey structure exhibits elements of Historicist architecture. The symmetrical façade is articulated by two oriels connected by balconies on the second and third floors. A stepped central pediment forms the principal compositional focus. The upper section is accentuated by profiled cornices and circular openings within the oriels. A distinctive feature of the building is the extensive terrace occupying the full footprint of the structure.</p><p>During the interwar period, V. Putvinskio Street acquired the nickname “the street of embassies” due to the presence of numerous foreign diplomatic missions. This designation was further reinforced by this building, which housed the Hungarian Consulate in apartment No. 4 between 1938 and 1939.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/18.jpg', '54.90084880', '23.91257130');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('19', 'Former House of Lawyer Kazimieras Škėma (now privately owned)', '1933, architects Bronius Elsbergas, Klaudijus Dušauskas-Duž |60  V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio g. 60', '<p>In 1932, lawyer Kazimieras Škėma, regarded as one of the wealthiest individuals of the interwar period, commissioned the construction of a residence in the prestigious Kalnų Street district. The initial design was prepared by architect Klaudijus Dušauskas-Duž; during construction, responsibility for the project was assumed by Bronius Elsbergas.</p><p>The most significant modification to the design was the addition of an extra storey. Five-storey residential buildings were rare in the temporary capital; consequently, the owner was required to obtain special approval from the Municipal Construction Commission for the buildings’ height, which exceeded the prevailing scale of development along V. Putvinskio Street.</p><p>The structure exhibits clear modernist tendencies: a five-storey volume with an asymmetrical façade, featuring oriels connected to balconies that echo the rounded geometry of the window bays. The ground floor contains two entrances, one serving as the principal access to the building and the other providing entry to the inner courtyard. Characteristic design elements associated with B. Elsbergas are also present, including profiled window surrounds and decorative mouldings. The inner façade is distinguished by broken-form balconies on the second to fifth floors. On the western side, the building adjoins the Antanas Gylys Hospital complex.</p><p>Upon completion, the house became one of the architectural symbols of modern Kaunas. Between 1934 and 1939, diplomatic delegations from Czechoslovakia and Sweden occupied premises within the building.</p>', '../../ehl-pastatai69e876fa5c3b1.jpg', '54.90087880', '23.91153930');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('20', 'The house of artist Antanas Žmuidzinavičius, part of the building complex (now – A. Žmuidzinavičius Creations and Collections Museum)', '1928, architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis | 64 V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio g. 64', '<p>During the interwar period, Kalnų Street (now V. Putvinskio Street) became a prestigious residential area for Lithuanias’ cultural and political elite. In 1928, the artist Antanas Žmuidzinavičius settled at No. 64 with his family. The two-storey house was designed by architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis, and a third storey was added approximately a decade later.</p><p>After moving in, the owners leased the ground floor to students, exiles, and socially disadvantaged residents, while occupying the second floor themselves. The upper floor served as the A. Žmuidzinavičius&#x27; creative studio. During the interwar period, the building also housed the Swedish Consulate; in 1930, the Finland-Swedish writer and poet Henry Parland worked there.</p><p>The building is characterised by an irregular plan incorporating two staircases. Distinctive features include undulating window forms, curved door openings, and balcony railings decorated with tulip motifs. The interior retains numerous refined details, including brightly painted floors in green and red tones, built-in wardrobes, recurring national decorative motifs, and coloured glass elements. These features, together with the original furnishings, have been preserved to the present day.
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('21', 'Kaunas Church of the Sacred Heart of Jesus', '1938, architects Algirdas Šalkauskis, Adolfas Netyksa, Pranas Markūnas | 60 A. Juozapavičiaus Ave.', 'A. Juozapavičiaus pr. 60', '<p>From the late 19th century, the district of Šančiai developed as a centre of industrial and military activity: it accommodated the largest military complex of the Kaunas Fortress, a major metalworks, and numerous workshops. This rapid development led to significant population growth and a corresponding need for a religious building.</p><p>The construction of the church during the interwar period was initiated by parish priest Mamertas Lumbė. The design process extended over several years: in 1935, architect Algirdas Šalkauskis submitted an initial project. Owing to disagreements with the client, the unfinished design was subsequently continued by architect Adolfas Netyksa. Construction of the modernist church was completed in 1937, and the building was consecrated in 1938.</p><p>Upon completion, the church became a prominent feature of the avenue, despite its restrained use of decorative elements. The architectural expression of the building combines modernist principles with Romanesque influences, often evoking the appearance of an industrial structure rather than a traditional place of worship. Its large volumes are harmoniously integrated into the surrounding urban environment of industrial facilities, infrastructure, and barracks complexes.</p><p>The building has a rectangular plan, with two low towers emphasising the central façade. Proportionally elevated sacristies attached to the side elevations further articulate the composition. The façades are defined by a disciplined arrangement of geometric forms: square entrance portals contrast with the vertical rhythm of narrow rectangular windows.</p><p>The roof structure employs a modern reinforced concrete system designed by engineer Pranas Markūnas and represents one of the earliest examples of thin-shell reinforced concrete construction in interwar Lithuania. Comparable structural solutions were also applied in the Physical Culture Palace and the Romuva Cinema.</p><p>Within the interior, notable artistic elements include the fresco Angels by Liudas Truikys, located in the presbytery arch, and stained-glass compositions by Stasys Ušinskas integrated into the rear façade.</p><p>The church sustained damage during wartime bombardments: the glazed rear façade was shattered and the altar was damaged. In 1942, the altar and rear wall were redesigned by architect Bronius Elsbergas.</p><p>The Church of the Sacred Heart of Jesus in Šančiai represents a characteristic example of restrained modern sacral architecture informed by a Romanesque idiom. Modernist churches were relatively rare during the period of the First Republic, rendering this building an especially significant and valuable example within the context of Lithuanian sacral heritage.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/21.jpg', '54.87168000', '23.93847740');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('22', 'Tulpė Cooperative House (now privately owned)', '1926, engineer Antanas Macijauskas | 15 A. Mickevičiaus St.', 'A. Mickevičiaus g. 15', '<p>Located in central Kaunas, the three-storey brick Tulpė (Tulip) house represents one of the earliest cooperative residential buildings in Lithuania. The building reflects early efforts to formulate a Lithuanian national architectural style through the adaptation of folk decorative motifs.</p><p>Designed in 1925 by engineer Antanas Macijauskas, the rectangular-plan structure comprised two spacious five-room apartments on each floor. The decorative programme was developed according to the architect’s distinctive interpretation of national style – abandoning neo-Baroque forms in favour of motifs derived from folk art.</p><p>The richly ornamented façade commands attention, conveying an aesthetic rooted in vernacular traditions, with stylised interpretations of craftsmen’s ornamentation, including tulip motifs, star-like forms, and serrated patterns. Executed in clay and plaster, the decorative elements represent an innovative attempt to translate the tradition of woodcarving into more durable materials. However, within less than a decade, such approaches attracted critical scrutiny, with commentators arguing that the transposition of folk motifs into masonry and plaster resulted in a distorted, even caricatured, expression: “In 1925–1926 in Kaunas, one individual, admittedly not an architect, attempted to express wooden ornamentation in masonry and plaster, but produced a caricature.”</p><p>The most elaborately treated section is the central part of the building, distinguished by a broad avant-corps. At the centre of the broken-form pediment is a circular window evoking the image of the sun. Below it, a crescent-shaped skylight illuminates the staircase. The remaining windows are framed by intricately profiled pediments (sandrics). The third floor is demarcated by a decorative cornice incorporating a wave motif and an additional pediment.</p><p>The Tulpė house remains a bold architectural experiment in Kaunas – a manifesto of the national style and a testament to the cultural dialogue between tradition and modernity.</p><p>23. Former House of Entrepreneur Jonas Lapėnas (now privately owned)</p><p>1932, architect Feliksas Vizbaras | 38 Kęstučio St.</p><p>One of the largest residential buildings and among the earliest skyscrapers in Kaunas belonged to the millionaire entrepreneur Jonas Lapėnas, director of the Maistas company and a prominent figure within the Nationalist Party. An influential economic leader, he also chaired the boards of Lietuvos muilas and Lietūkis and was among the founders of the Pažanga publishing house and the Vilkolakis theatre.</p><p>The six-storey rental apartment building, designed by architect Feliksas Vizbaras, was constructed in 1932–1933 to the highest standards of the interwar period, incorporating central heating, running water, sewage systems, and two lifts. The architectural composition integrates national decorative elements with modern stylistic principles.</p><p>High-quality finishing materials, typically reserved for public buildings, were employed, including granite render for the walls and polished brown granite for the entrances. The principal façade is articulated by horizontal bands of dark plaster, complemented by windows with decorative detailing and metal balcony railings. This combination created an impression of opulence, establishing the building as a benchmark of residential luxury in interwar Kaunas.</p><p>The structure is symmetrical, with a central section crowned by a stepped attic and flanked by five-storey avant-corps. The main and service staircases are separated by a decorative glazed partition, ensuring a clear functional division between representative and service areas. The principal living spaces of the apartments were oriented towards Kęstučio Street, while the courtyard side accommodated kitchens with refrigerated storage, servants’ quarters, and bedrooms.</p><p>The ground floor, featuring large display windows, was dedicated to retail functions, while the upper floors contained residential units. In total, the building comprised eight five-room apartments. Additional service spaces, including storage areas, garages, and drivers’ quarters, were constructed in the courtyard. The sixth floor was designed for communal use, including a hall with a fireplace and a caretaker’s apartment located within the attic. A number of original interior elements, including the lobby furnishings, have been preserved.</p><p>From the summer of 1938 until September 1939, the Polish Legation occupied the building, securing its place in the diplomatic history of Kaunas. By combining two apartments, a nine-room representative suite was created for this purpose. A commemorative plaque on the façade attests to this period.</p><p>The building has also entered literary history, serving as one of the principal settings in V. Sirijos Giras’ novel Raudonmedžio rojus (Mahogany Paradise).</p><p>During the early Soviet period, following nationalisation, the building was adapted for use as a dormitory for the Agricultural Academy and later as a research institute. Today, it accommodates office functions and has regained its status as a prestigious location for business and community activity.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/22.jpg', '54.89616680', '23.91719280');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('24', 'Former House of Pranas Gudavičius and Aleksandra Iljinienė', '1933, architect Arnas Funkas | 19 K. Donelaičio St.', 'K. Donelaičio g. 19', '<p>The two-storey residence of Aleksandra and Jurgis Iljinas is regarded as one of the most significant examples of interwar Lithuanian Modernism and an architectural icon of Kaunas. In 1933, J. Iljinas acquired the plot together with a design prepared by architect Arnas Funkas from military physician Pranas Gudavičius and presented it as a gift to his wife. Remarkably, the construction of the house was completed within a period of just ten months.</p><p>The building is distinguished by its architectural expressiveness, particularly in its innovative window composition, which includes corner glazing, curved glass elements, and a prominent circular window set within a projecting oriel above the entrance, rising to a height exceeding five metres. The house was also notable for its refined and distinctive Art Deco interior.</p><p>The Iljinas family resided on the second floor. Their apartment was characterised by a high degree of luxury and an Oriental aesthetic, with interiors and furnishings designed by A. Funkas. A niche incorporating a traditional muqarnas element – a decorative feature associated with Islamic architecture – has been preserved.</p><p>The building retains numerous other authentic details, including spiral wooden staircases, stained-glass doors, arched openings with wooden panelling, and refined ceiling ornamentation. A recreational terrace was created on the roof, incorporating a small orangery or winter garden, visible through the glazed ceiling of the hall. One of the most distinctive original features, however, has not survived.</p><p>Two rental apartments were located on the ground floor. During the interwar period, these were occupied by Mykolas Golbinderis and Jurgis Matulaitis, while Grigorijus Ickavičius resided in the basement. In 1941, the building was nationalised during the Second World War. Following the departure of the Iljinas family to Germany, the apartment was occupied by the singer Gražina Matulaitytė and her husband, the journalist, poet, and art historian Aleksis Rannit.</p><p>During the Soviet period, the building accommodated various institutions, including the Voluntary Society for Cooperation with the Army, Air Force, and Navy, as well as fire protection services.</p><p>In 2018, the building underwent a meticulous restoration, reinstating the character of interwar Modernism. The original proportions and both exterior and interior details were carefully preserved, including the refined window forms, wooden elements, and Art Deco features. The previously grey façade was restored to a lighter colour scheme.</p><p>The building is currently accessible to visitors through organised private tours.</p><p>__________________________________________</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/24.jpg', '54.89848740', '23.92219800');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('25', 'Former House of Burgomaster Jonas Vileišis (now privately owned)', '1930, architect Aleksandras Gordevičius | 68 V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio g. 68', '<p>Jonas Vileišis, long-serving Burgomaster of Kaunas from 1921 to 1931, played a decisive role in the modernisation of the city during the interwar period. Under his leadership, Kaunas was transformed into a city of European standard: modern sewage and water supply systems were introduced, streets were paved, bridges were constructed, public transport infrastructure was developed, funiculars were installed, and thousands of new buildings were erected. Vileišis drew inspiration from both the United States and major European cities during his diplomatic missions.</p><p>He initiated the construction of this residential building on his own plot in the prestigious V. Putvinskio Street. Part of the building was intended for rental purposes. Between 1934 and 1938, the house gained particular prominence as the location of the Legation of the United States of America, headed by Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary Owen J. C. Norem. After leasing the property to the legation, the owner relocated to a house constructed at the rear of the plot in 1932 (currently at 66 V. Putvinskio St.).</p><p>Several design iterations were developed before the final version was approved. Technical supervision of construction was carried out by architect Aleksandras Gordevičius, who is also regarded as the principal author of the realised design.</p><p>The building’s architecture features distinct elements of Modernism and the so-called “American” Streamline aesthetic. The large three-story building consists of two wings with an irregular layout—the larger one facing the street and the narrower one on the courtyard side. The main reception areas are arranged around a central hall, and a so-called “light well” has been installed next to the firewall to ensure natural light.</p><p>The main entrance is positioned laterally, accessed via the driveway leading into the courtyard. The most expressive exterior accent is the recessed and elevated corner volume with rounded balconies, forming a streamlined and dynamic silhouette. On the upper floors, the corner section is articulated by graphic horizontal banding, while the street façade is structured by inter-floor bands framed with profiled mouldings.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/25.jpg', '54.90096030', '23.91037030');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('26', 'Former Villa of the Prime Minister of the Republic of Lithuania Juozas Tūbelis (now – Kaunas School of Art)', '1933, architect Feliksas Vizbaras | 1 Dainavos St.', 'Dainavos g. 1', '<p>One of the most distinguished interwar Modernist villas in Kaunas is the former residence of Prime Minister Juozas Tūbelis, situated on the crest of the Žaliakalnis slope near the Kaukas Stairs. The building was carefully integrated into the topography, with its composition oriented to maximise panoramic views over Kaunas.</p><p>The residence, inhabited by J. Tūbelis and his wife, the public figure Jadvyga Chodakauskaitė-Tūbelienė, is characterised by an asymmetrical and dynamically composed volume. Architect F. Vizbaras conceived a modern yet representative villa – a plastered brick structure of two and three storeys, incorporating a semi-circular veranda, balconies, terraces, and a pitched roof.</p><p>The strict geometric articulation is enriched by dark plaster window surrounds, pronounced cornices, and refined veranda detailing. Among the principal compositional accents are the semi-cylindrical veranda and the corner turret, which impart a sense of light monumentality. The internal layout follows a free plan: spaces are arranged around a central stair hall, while the principal rooms facing the slope are unified into a spacious representative hall intended for receptions and official gatherings.</p><p>During the interwar period, the villa functioned not only as a private residence but also as a significant centre of political and social life. It hosted members of the Kaunas intelligentsia, foreign diplomats, high-ranking state officials, and President Antanas Smetona with his family. The close familial relationship between Sofija Smetonienė and Jadvyga Tūbelienė, who were sisters, further reinforced the social significance of the gatherings held here. Discussions within this milieu included progressive ideas, such as advocacy for women’s suffrage, at a time when such rights were not yet universally established in countries like France or Italy.</p><p>The interior reflected the elevated social status of the occupants, with spacious rooms, refined furnishings, and artworks contributing to a representative domestic environment.</p><p>The house was nationalised during the early Soviet occupation, and since 1946 it has accommodated an art school, now known as the Kaunas Art Gymnasium. The building’s functional clarity and aesthetic expressiveness continue to provide a suitable environment for creative education.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/26.jpg', '54.90081820', '23.92410060');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('27', 'Former House of Contractor Mikas Grodzenskis (now privately owned)', '1929, architects Edmundas Frykas, Mikas Grodzenskis | 17 K. Donelaičio St.', 'K. Donelaičio g. 17', '<p>One of the earliest Modernist residential buildings in Kaunas was constructed on K. Donelaičio Street. Its owner and developer, contractor Mikas Grodzenskis, prepared the design in collaboration with architect Edmundas Frykas and supervised the construction process.</p><p>The building is distinguished by its restrained architectural language. It is characterised by clear geometric forms, smooth surfaces, and a near absence of decorative elements. Such an approach reflects the core principles of early Modernism – functionality, rationality, and economy of means.</p><p>The spatial organisation is both rational and functional. The building accommodated not only residential units but also the owner’s office. A street-facing entrance led directly to a ground-floor office connected to the apartment. In contrast, the principal residential entrance was recessed along the driveway, effectively separating the living quarters from street noise.</p><p>The asymmetrical composition of the house is expressed through a stepped and fragmented façade. A slight setback from the street line introduces a sense of spatial dynamism. The first recess accommodates the entrance and a balcony, while the second incorporates the driveway leading into the courtyard.</p><p>A distinctive feature is the so-called “Italian courtyard” located at the rear. This enclosed space, defined by a high boundary wall, incorporates paving and a terrace, representing a rare typological solution in Kaunas residential architecture.</p><p>Corner windows, a hallmark of 1930s Modernism, constitute one of the building’s most expressive features. They enhance the sense of lightness, increase daylight penetration, and emphasise the modern architectural character.</p><p>The building thus exemplifies the dissemination of modern architectural ideas and reflects both the ambitions of a private client and the professional competence of a construction specialist.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/27.jpg', '54.89848510', '23.92242680');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('28', 'Former House of Engineer Antanas Gravrogkas (now privately owned)', '1932, architect Edmundas Frykas | 70 V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio 70', '<p>The residence of engineer and former Burgomaster of Kaunas Antanas Gravrogkas, constructed in 1932, represents one of the few residential commissions by architect Edmundas Frykas, who was distinguished by a unique style within Lithuanian architecture. The building reflects his distinctive synthesis of Modernist and Historicist tendencies.</p><p>This four-storey structure is notable for its richly articulated decorative programme, incorporating elements of both Historicism and Art Deco. The principal façade is divided into vertically differentiated sections, each treated with a distinct compositional approach. The three lower storeys are emphasised by articulated projections, culminating in a terrace above the third floor, enclosed by a classical balustrade. This terrace visually links the central lower volume with the taller lateral sections of the façade.</p><p>The left portion of the façade, marking the entrance to the plot, is rounded, while the main entrance is located on the right-hand side. Although not prominently accentuated architecturally, the entrance is distinguished by sculptural decoration. Bronze bas-reliefs created in 1933 by sculptor Juozas Zikaras – The Horse Tamer, The Mower, and The Gleaner – depict agrarian and mythological motifs derived from folk tradition. Folk art influences are further evident in the floral ornamentation of the balconies on the second and third floors.</p><p>Each floor contained a single apartment with a relatively complex spatial layout. A roof terrace, enclosed by a balustrade and crowned with a decorative serrated parapet, completes the composition. The courtyard façade retains projecting cold-storage cupboards of the oriel type, a characteristic feature of interwar residential architecture in Kaunas.</p><p>The building remains one of the most striking examples of decorative interwar architecture in the city.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/28.jpg', '54.90095320', '23.91012850');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('29', 'Former House of Entrepreneurs Moses and Malka Chaimson (now privately owned)', '1930–1931, architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis | 13 Maironio St.', 'Maironio g. 13', '<p>Entrepreneur Moses Chaimson, co-owner of a textile warehouse, commissioned the construction of a residential building together with his brother, selecting architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis, recently returned from studies in Rome, to design the project. Completed in 1930, the building represented an exceptionally modern apartment house and became the tallest residential structure in Kaunas at the time.</p><p>Its austere exterior, characterised by deliberately restrained forms, was atypical within the context of interwar Lithuanian architecture. The principal façade composition is based on balanced proportions, with the axis of symmetry accentuated by a prominent oriel extending from the second floor to the attic level.</p><p>The laconic portal with a lintel is framed by a lightly profiled granite plaster molding. A tall base, prominent cornices, and wide windows of varying sizes, divided into vertical sections, create a rhythm of horizontal lines. The corner bay windows are glazed with curved glass.</p><p>The floor plan is rectangular, with a bay window featuring a wavy outline on the courtyard side. This is typical of apartment buildings from the 1930s. The building has two stairwells: the main one, which includes an elevator, and a service stairwell hidden behind a glass partition.</p><p>The first three floors each contained two spacious luxury apartments, featuring generous entrance halls, double-aspect layouts, and direct connections between reception rooms and dining areas. The fourth and fifth floors accommodated four smaller apartments each.</p><p>Service quarters were located in the semi-basement and attic mezzanine, reflecting contemporary social hierarchies in residential planning.</p><p>The Chaimson family occupied an apartment on the third floor, while one of the fifth-floor units was rented by the noted artist and scenographer Mstislavas Dobužinskis.</p><p>Owing to its modernity, functional organisation, and level of comfort, the building remains comparable to contemporary residential developments in Kaunas.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/29.jpg', '54.89692670', '23.90929530');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('30', 'Former House of Vincas and Ona Tercijonas (now privately owned)', '1936, architect Bronius Elsbergas|72  V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio g. 72', '<p>During the interwar period, the prestigious area surrounding Kalnų Street attracted prominent public figures, physicians, and lawyers, whose residences collectively formed a cohesive architectural ensemble. The house of Vincas and Ona Tercijonas, positioned at the terminal point of the street, functions as either the beginning or the culmination of this ensemble, depending on the direction of approach.</p><p>The building is distinguished by its dual spatial structure and its sensitive adaptation to the sloping terrain of Žaliakalnis. From the street, it presents itself as a compact three-storey modernist urban residence, whereas from the courtyard it assumes the character of a villa-like structure: part of the third floor is covered by a steep pitched roof, and the ground floor is partially embedded into the slope, supported by a retaining wall with a narrow terrace.</p><p>The composition is asymmetrical and characterised by laconic forms. The street façade is dominated by wide windows, a corner oriel on the second floor, and continuous balconies extending across the façade. The rounded corners of these elements soften the strict geometry and lend the building a sense of modernist lightness.</p><p>The internal layout was rationally organised and tailored to the needs of the occupants. Two similarly planned apartments were arranged on both the ground and first floors, while the upper levels were connected by an internal staircase into a single residential unit. The owners – paediatrician Vincas Tercijonas and his wife Ona – resided in the house.</p><p>The building was adapted for medical practice: visitor spaces were separated near the entrance, and sanitary facilities were integrated within the shared staircases. Ona Putvinskaitė-Tercijonienė, an educator and public figure, was likewise highly active in civic life, contributing to public health, education, publishing, and organisational work, and playing a leading role in women’s riflemen’s organisations and national committees.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/30.jpg', '54.90093530', '23.90984580');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('31', 'House of Physicians Paulina Kalvaitytė and Vladas Lašas (now privately owned)', '1933, architect Stasys Kudokas |3 Laisvės Ave.', 'Laisvės al. 3', '<p>Situated at the entrance to Laisvės Avenue, at the intersection with Trakų Street and near the steps leading towards Vytautas Park, the building is notable for its distinctive Netherlandish-inspired façade. Behind its unusually thick walls operated one of the earliest X-ray facilities in Lithuania.</p><p>Constructed in 1933 according to the design of S. Kudokas, the building is highly expressive: arch-shaped surrounds are decorated with stylised “tulip” motifs, while white-highlighted window frames contrast with the darker background. The absence of a conventional plinth and the elevated wall plane conceal a pitched roof. Although the upper silhouette is stepped, the overall composition reads as a unified surface, articulated by a central axis and a tall staircase window accentuated by relief arches.</p><p>The building has a rectangular, symmetrical plan with a double-loaded corridor system and two staircases. One serves as the principal staircase, while the second, located on the courtyard side, functions as a service staircase. Balconies are attached to the latter, facilitating circulation for domestic staff and enabling the separation of service and representative functions.</p><p>The house belonged to prominent medical professionals – Professor Vladas Lašas, founder of the Kaunas Clinics, and Paulina Kalvaitytė-Karvelienė, one of the first Lithuanian radiologists. Her private X-ray practice operated on the ground floor, employing one of the earliest X-ray machines in the country. She also headed the radiology department of Kaunas City Hospital and lectured at the Faculty of Medicine of Vytautas Magnus University.</p><p>In 1938, ownership of the house was transferred to Vladas Lašas, a physician-physiologist and pioneer of allergology in Lithuania, although he did not reside there.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/31.jpg', '54.89659410', '23.92673760');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('32', 'House of Entrepreneur Mina Kotkauskienė (now privately owned)', '1930, Bronius Elsbergas | 69 Laisvės Ave.', 'Laisvės al. 69', '<p>Located in the central section of Laisvės Avenue, this building initially appears restrained; however, its dynamic façade composition becomes apparent upon closer observation.</p><p>The expressive effect is generated by a zigzagging wall plane and projecting balconies that articulate the façade in a rhythmic manner. Inter-floor bands further reinforce this angular composition, while a parapet frieze crowns the building. The architectural language reflects an Expressionist interpretation of Art Deco.</p><p>The house was constructed in 1930 on commission from the entrepreneur Mina Kotkauskienė, who managed the nearby Olimp cinema, later renamed Rambynas.</p><p>The functional arrangement follows the typical pattern of Laisvės Avenue: commercial premises occupy the ground floor, while residential units are located above. Four shops with separate street entrances were installed at ground level, with four apartments arranged on the upper floors. A single, narrow staircase, illuminated by a courtyard-facing window, serves the building.</p><p>Over time, the house acquired cultural significance. Between 1942 and 1949, it was the residence of the composer, conductor, and cultural figure Juozas Tallat-Kelpša, who at the time directed the nearby Kaunas State Drama Theatre. A commemorative plaque with a bas-relief dedicated to him is affixed to the façade.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/32.jpg', '54.89724990', '23.91095000');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('33', 'House of Taubė-Fiegė Elšteinienė (now – the Office of the Representative of the Government of the Republic of Lithuania)', '1935, architects Leiba Zimanas, Izaokas Trakmanas | 4 L. Sapiegos St.', 'L. Sapiegos g. 4', '<p>During the interwar period, a refined modern residence belonging to Taubė-Fiegė Elšteinienė was constructed on present-day L. Sapiegos Street. Designed by architects Leiba Zimanas and Izaokas Trakmanas, the building became a distinctive urban landmark due to its restrained yet expressive façade reflecting Bauhaus principles.</p><p>The white surface is rhythmically articulated by narrow windows and complemented by a contrasting dark plaster band. A corner loggia supported by a column introduces a distinctive compositional element, originally intended to accommodate a sculptural feature. At a later stage, a third floor was added to enhance functional capacity.</p><p>The interior comprised five apartments: two smaller units on the first and third floors, and a spacious owner’s residence occupying the second floor. Moses Elstein, the owner’s husband, operated a perfumery and cosmetics business, and the family enjoyed a high standard of modern domestic comfort.</p><p>Shortly after completion, the building received formal recognition: in 1936, it was awarded a prize by the Kaunas Municipal Construction Department for the most distinguished residential façade. This accolade reflects both the architects’ skill and the evolving modernist aesthetic of the period.</p><p>During the Soviet era, the building was nationalised and adapted for administrative use. Today, it remains an important element of Kaunas architectural heritage, having served in recent years as the headquarters of the Government Representative in Kaunas County.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/33.jpg', '54.89855540', '23.90635740');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('34', 'House of Elijošius Šneideris (now privately owned)', '1938, architect Stasys Kudokas | 3 Vaidilutės St.', 'Vaidilutės g. 3', '<p>An exceptional multi-apartment residential building was constructed in 1938 within a small cul-de-sac between Kęstučio and Miško Streets. The four-storey structure built in 1938 is distinguished by its refined proportions and elegant architectural expression, and is widely regarded as one of the most accomplished examples of mature interwar Modernism in Kaunas.</p><p>Remarkably, the building was completed within a period of six months. To reduce the perceived height, the uppermost floor was designed with a reduced footprint, creating a lighter overall silhouette.</p><p>The composition features a mansard roof, asymmetrical massing, and projecting volumes that contribute to a dynamic spatial expression. Horizontal, rounded balconies dominate the façades, enhancing the impression of lightness and refinement. A prominent oriel with narrow windows and decorative cornices accentuates the vertical axis of the staircase.</p><p>The building comprises eleven spacious apartments, typically two per floor, each consisting of three or four rooms. Interior planning prioritised functionality: representative rooms were interconnected by folding doors, while service spaces, including maid’s rooms, were located adjacent to kitchens on the courtyard side. Notably, the design accorded particular attention to service staff, with maid’s rooms provided with small private balconies. The building was equipped with a lift, and a separate service staircase was omitted, resulting in a shared circulation system for all occupants.</p><p>As in other works by S. Kudokas, a coherent architectural language is evident, incorporating subtle decorative motifs such as floral rosettes, recalling interior elements of the Kaunas Officers’ Club.</p><p>The original owner, Elijošius Šneideris, and his family occupied the building only briefly, as they were deported by Soviet authorities to the Tomsk region in 1941.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/34.jpg', '54.89478510', '23.92302410');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('35', 'Villa of Česlovas Pacevičius (now privately owned)', '1934, architect Vsevolodas Kopylovas |59  Vydūno Ave.', 'Vydūno al. 59', '<p>A compact yet expressive villa in Žaliakalnis represents one of the few surviving examples of minimalist interwar architecture in Kaunas. The rectangular, single-storey residential volume is defined by its laconic composition and precisely calibrated proportions. Its architectural language reflects Modernist principles associated with Ludwig Mies van der Rohe, the prominent architect, academic, and interior designer.</p><p>The principal façade is strictly symmetrical and formally restrained: a centrally placed entrance is flanked by two large windows. The recessed entrance niche, with softly rounded corners, is clad in yellow ceramic tiles guiding movement towards the doorway. A subtle horizontal canopy and a narrow cornice articulate the portal, while window openings are framed by slightly raised plaster reveals matching the ceramic tone. Even the ventilation apertures on the side elevations are treated as deliberate graphic elements.</p><p>The building remains ascetic in expression, yet achieves a sense of monumentality through its scale and unbroken planar surfaces. From the street, the structure appears to have a flat roof, although it is in fact mono-pitched, sloping gently towards the courtyard and concealed behind parapets.</p><p>The surrounding environment is defined by a carefully designed fence with diagonally fixed boards, where shifting shadows introduce visual dynamism. The entrance composition is reinforced by masonry gate posts and a light pergola, together forming a unified architectural ensemble.</p><p>The interior was organised as a compact yet functionally efficient three-room apartment. In the interwar period, both interior and exterior were governed by principles of rationality and formal clarity: representative rooms faced the street, while service spaces were oriented towards the courtyard.</p><p>The villa was constructed in Žaliakalnis, a garden-city district developed in the interwar period, characterised by open, detached residential planning. Within this context, minimalist modernism contrasted sharply with surrounding traditional villas, introducing a new architectural paradigm.</p><p>The building received official recognition: in 1935, the Kaunas City Council awarded it a prize “for the most aesthetically and functionally successful brick residence”.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/35.jpg', '54.90385020', '23.94711850');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('36', 'Residential House of Juozas Daugirdas (now privately owned)', '1930, architect Vladimiras Dubeneckis | 30 Vytauto Ave.', 'Vytauto pr. 30', '<p>Commissioned by Juozas Daugirdas, director of the Drobė company and Lithuanian-American entrepreneur, the building comprises a four-storey apartment house with commercial premises on Vytauto Avenue. Intended for rental purposes, it became a prominent architectural accent along this major urban artery during the interwar period. This late work by V. Dubeneckis reflects the architect’s transition from academic classicism towards architectural modernism.</p><p>The building volume is symmetrical and organised around a centrally placed stairwell and lift core. The main façade is articulated by two prominent oriels intersected with ribbon windows and fine vertical subdivisions. The attic storeys above accentuate the recessed central composition.</p><p>While the overall design is dominated by Modernist principles, decorative elements retain the architect’s individual stylistic references, including stylised folk tulips above the entrance.</p><p>The ground floor was designated for commercial use, with large display windows representing a technical advancement in interwar Lithuania. The second to fourth floors contained two spacious five-room apartments per level, while smaller units were located in the attic. The Daugirdas family resided on the third floor. Apartment layouts were functionally structured, with representative rooms oriented towards Vytauto Avenue and private quarters facing the courtyard.</p><p>The building also acquired urban significance. In the 1920s, this section of Vytauto Avenue was characterised by stark contrasts between deteriorating wooden houses and emerging brick constructions. The Daugirdas house became a symbol of urban modernisation, contributing to the transformation of the district into a representative residential area. French Consul Paul Py also resided in the building for a period, further underscoring its prestigious status.</p><p>During the Soviet period, the building was nationalised: commercial premises continued on the ground floor, while apartments were converted into dormitory-style accommodation, significantly altering the original spatial organisation. Despite subsequent alterations and visible deterioration, the building remains an important monument of interwar Kaunas architecture.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/36.jpg', '54.88973600', '23.92675900');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('37', 'The Butas Company Apartment Building (now privately owned)', '1932, architect Jonas Kriščiukaitis | 5 Trakų St.', 'Trakų g. 5', '<p>In interwar Kaunas, residential buildings were developed not only by individual clients but also by associations and professional collectives. One such example is the apartment building on Trakų Street, constructed in 1932 by senior officials of the Supreme Tribunal of Lithuania, who formed one of the earliest housing cooperatives under the simple name Butas (The Apartment).</p><p>Among its members were writer and legal scholar, Supreme Tribunal president Prof. Antanas Kriščiukaitis (Aišbė); engineers Jonas and Kazys Kriščiukaičiai; and lawyer, public figure, Kaunas City Council member, and Lutheran pastor Mykolas Kavolis, father of sociologist Vytautas Kavolis. The architect of the building, Jonas Kriščiukaitis, also resided in the property.</p><p>The site was selected in a quiet yet strategically advantageous location near the city centre, on the slopes of Vytautas Park, at a time when Trakų Street was still under development. This setting enabled a balance between private life and professional activity while avoiding the intensity of the urban core.</p><p>Spatial planning accommodated diverse needs: two small apartments for service staff were located on the ground floor with direct access from the driveway, while spacious five-room apartments occupied the upper levels. These were organised according to clear functional zoning, separating public, private, and service areas. Office spaces and separate sanitary facilities for clients were placed adjacent to reception areas, ensuring the privacy of domestic life. A centrally located elevator, an advanced and rare feature for the period, was installed between the main and service staircases.</p><p>The building’s construction was innovative: engineer A. Rozenbliumas employed a monolithic reinforced concrete frame, a rare solution in interwar residential architecture in Lithuania. As a result, the building attracted significant public attention.</p><p>The façade composition is restrained and orderly, defined by symmetry, a vertical stairwell window marking the central axis, and rhythmically arranged wide openings. Its Modernist character is reinforced by curved oriels emerging from the second floor, with rounded corner windows and adjacent balconies. Tall, narrow stairwell windows, often referred to as “thermometers”, became a distinctive feature of this and other interwar modernist apartment buildings.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/37.jpg', '54.89623060', '23.92815050');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('38', 'Aleksotas Funicular', '1935, The equipment was manufactured and installed by the company THEODOR BELL und Cie. | 6 Amerikos Lietuvių St.', 'Amerikos Lietuvių g. 6', '<p>Kaunas is the only city in the Baltic States with two surviving interwar funiculars, of which the Aleksotas lift is among the most distinctive symbols of the city. In 2025, the Aleksotas funicular marked its 90th anniversary. Over time, it has retained its functional and cultural relevance: it serves both as a tourist attraction and as a practical urban transport link integral to Kaunas’s identity.</p><p>It is also regarded as one of the most significant examples of the Architecture of Optimism. The structure accentuates Kaunas’s topographical character, highlighting the interaction between the city and its natural landscape. The line connects the Old Town with Aleksotas Hill and its observation platform, offering one of the most expansive panoramas of the city.</p><p>The carriages were manufactured by the Kaunas-based company Amlit in cooperation with Swiss engineers. In approximately 25 seconds, the funicular ascends a 133-metre track at an incline of 18 degrees. From its inception, it incorporated advanced safety systems, including automatic braking mechanisms activated in the event of cable failure. Each carriage accommodates up to 25 passengers, with a lifting capacity of 2,000 kilograms.</p><p>Contemporary press accounts recorded its significance in daily urban life: “The Aleksotas funicular carries a thousand passengers a day, makes 200 trips, and receives 79,80 LTL in revenue”. The first passengers were the ministers and burgomasters of the time, and the opening ceremonies and first journeys were even filmed.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/38.jpg', '54.89099380', '23.88697310');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('39', 'Former Antanas Gylys Hospital Building (now privately owned)', '1933, architect Leonas Ritas | 62 V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio g. 62', '<p>One building with two advanced functions. This phrase aptly describes the structure designed by L. Ritas in 1933 on prestigious V. Putvinskio Street, which combined a modern clinic for internal and nervous diseases with the private residence of its owner, physician, Doctor of Philosophy, and public figure Antanas Gylys on the fourth floor.</p><p>After studying internal medicine and psychiatry in Moscow and Munich, A. Gylys returned to Lithuania in 1924 and lectured at the Faculty of Theology and Philosophy of Vytautas Magnus University. In 1934, he withdrew from academic work and, following the construction of this purpose-built facility, devoted himself entirely to private medical practice. The hospital quickly became one of the most advanced medical institutions in interwar Lithuania.</p><p>The architecture is defined by ascetic form, functional clarity, and restrained aesthetics. The volumetric composition is enlivened by an asymmetrical tower-like avant-corps, while large, regularly spaced windows ensure optimal lighting and meet contemporary hygienic standards. A mezzanine level and open terrace functioned as both recreational space and a viewing platform over New Town.</p><p>The internal organisation is clearly hierarchical: hydrotherapy facilities were located on the ground floor, consultation rooms on the second, and inpatient wards on the third. Departments for hydrotherapy, heliotherapy, and physiotherapy were equipped with advanced medical technology comparable to Western European clinics. The plan is of mixed type, and the main entrance is positioned from the driveway rather than the street, ensuring privacy for patients and staff.</p><p>Although the building is now privately owned and no longer serves medical purposes, significant original interior elements and technical equipment have been preserved. The original Swiss Schindler lift remains operational; hydrotherapy installations, a Peltz safe, and external wooden blinds designed for solar control are still extant.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/39.jpg', '54.90089690', '23.91130010');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('40', 'Šančiai Gymnasium (now – KTU Vaižgantas Progymnasium)', '1938, architect Stasys Kudokas | 27 Skuodo St.', 'Skuodo g. 27', '<p>Šančiai Gymnasium is one of the most significant examples of interwar Lithuanian modernist school architecture, designed by Stasys Kudokas. It is considered the architect’s second most important work after the Officers’ Club (Karininkų ramovė) and reflects his mature professional vision and innovative approach to public architecture.</p><p>Construction began in the summer of 1937 and was completed in September 1938. The total cost exceeded 1 million LTL, making it one of the largest and best-equipped educational institutions in 1930s Lithuania.</p><p>Although the location in Aukštieji Šančiai initially generated debate, the completed building was received with considerable public approval. During the interwar period, overcrowding in urban gymnasiums created urgent demand for new facilities, and this institution represented a major infrastructural advancement. Approximately 16 classes operated within the building, educating around 600 students.</p><p>The architectural composition reflects contemporary educational Modernism: functional planning, structural clarity, and restrained formal expression. The façade is defined by a rhythmic arrangement of windows and vertical elements, set upon a dark granite plinth rising to the first-floor level.</p><p>The main entrance is emphasised by a projecting avant-corps with recessed granite half-columns. Brackets above the entrances were intended to support sculptural elements. The monumentality of the composition is reinforced by broad, double-flight staircases. A striking formal contrast is created by a semi-cylindrical stairwell volume articulated through small square windows.</p><p>The building continues to serve its original purpose as the KTU Vaižgantas Progymnasium. Notable Lithuanian cultural and scientific figures educated here include Eduardas Mieželaitis, Janina Degutytė, Monika Mironaitė, among others.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/40.jpg', '54.87724210', '23.94199500');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('41', 'Pasaka Cinema (now – Nautilus Entertainment and Leisure Center)', '1939–1940, architects Jokūbas Rabinavičius, Juozas Segalauskas | 124 Savanorių Ave.', 'Savanorių pr. 124', '<p>The Pasaka cinema was among the last interwar cinema projects completed in Kaunas before the Soviet occupation. It opened its doors to the public on March 8, 1940, and the first screenings featured the Lithuanian newsreel and reviews produced by the American film distribution company Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer. This reflects the theatres’ ambition to be modern and to keep pace with the trends in film culture of the time.</p><p>The building is characterised by a narrow, elongated volume extending deep into the plot, resulting in a less than optimal auditorium configuration. Design interventions were introduced to mitigate spatial limitations. A multi-curved floor profile was installed, and seating was divided into separate sectors with independent access points. A carefully developed sightline and seating scheme ensured acceptable viewing conditions.</p><p>The cinema accommodated 487 seats: 353 in the stalls, 21 in box seating arranged in tiers, and 113 in the balcony. A narrow, corridor-like foyer was installed on the eastern side of the building, and shops operated along the street on both sides of the vestibule, supplementing the building&#x27;s functionality and providing it with more vitality.</p><p>The imperfections of the plan were compensated for by expressive architecture. The facade reflects the Art Deco stylistic trends prevalent in cinema construction during the 1930s, characterised by dynamism and momentum. The representative yet laconic main facade is formed by vertical projections that frame the central, elevated part of the building and connect it to the lateral volumes via stepped segments.</p><p>The architectural impression was strengthened by the illuminated PASAKA cinema sign, illuminating tubes, a stepped terrace silhouette, and vertically oriented ribs. The entrance is recessed into an open porch, whose profiled edges echoed the rhythm of the stairs, while a decorative balcony also functioned as a canopy.</p><p>Unlike the contemporaneous Romuva cinema, films were only screened at the Pasaka for approximately a decade. During the Soviet period, the building was repurposed for sports activities by the Medical Institute. In the 1960s, cinema use was briefly reinstated with a 420-seat auditorium, although this function was short-lived. As with many Kaunas cinemas, the Pasaka eventually ceased operations. In the early 21st century, the building was reconstructed and adapted for nightclub use.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/41.jpg', '54.90591780', '23.92206139');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('42', 'Building of the Vatican Diplomatic Mission (Nunciature) (now – Kaunas Artists House)', '1930, architect Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis | 56 V. Putvinskio St.', 'V. Putvinskio g. 56', '<p>Kalnų (V. Putvinskio) Street, one encounters building No. 56, today housing the Kaunas Artists’ House, an active cultural institution. Following Kaunas’s designation as the provisional capital, the building acquired an unexpected historical trajectory.</p><p>It is the only building in Kaunas commissioned by the Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the Republic of Lithuania specifically for a foreign diplomatic mission, the Vatican Nunciature. Designed in 1930 by Vytautas Landsbergis-Žemkalnis, it occupies a prominent position within Lithuanian interwar architecture.</p><p>The villa is set on a Žaliakalnis slope, recessed from the street, despite contemporary regulations favouring continuous perimeter development. An exception was granted for this representative structure, allowing a villa-like composition referencing Italian Renaissance typologies.</p><p>The asymmetrical massing is defined by substantial yet visually light volumes, articulated through a prominent cornice, terrace with external stairs, and clear planar façades. The interior was designed with functional flexibility: the ground floor contained chancery, offices, salon, dining room, and winter garden. Sliding partitions enabled spatial reconfiguration into a single ceremonial hall when required. The upper floor accommodated private quarters and a chapel.</p><p>Due to political circumstances, the Nunciature was never established in the building. It was rapidly repurposed, and by 1932 a children’s hospital operated within the premises. During the Soviet period, the building housed a tuberculosis dispensary and kindergarten and was also used as a polling station. Since 1971, the city&#x27;s Cultural Department has been located in the building, and shortly thereafter, the well-known space – the Kaunas Artists&#x27; House – was born. Today it is regarded as one of the longest continuously operating cultural institutions in Lithuania. Here, architecture, history, and contemporary artistic practice converge within a single spatial framework.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/42.jpg', '54.90096010', '23.91219000');
INSERT INTO `buildings_en` (`id`, `buildingName`, `buildingAuthor`, `buildingAddress`, `buildingDescription`, `imageSrc`, `latitude`, `longitude`) VALUES ('43', 'The House of Architect Stasys Kudokas', '1938, architect Stasys Kudokas | 11 V. Mykolaičio-Putino St.', 'V. Mykolaičio-Putino g. 11', '<p>The house designed by S. Kudokas embodies not only the prevailing architectural tendencies of the period, but also his own design philosophy, in which rational construction and artistic expression are treated as a unified system.</p><p>The only Lithuanian architect of the interwar period to hold a doctorate in architecture, obtained in Milan, he selected a complex yet highly expressive site on the steep slopes of Vytautas Hill for his residence. Owing to the pronounced topography, the interior is organised across shifted floor levels, incorporating multiple mezzanines and split-level spatial transitions. The rectangular volumetric composition is articulated through projections, loggias, galleries, and arcaded passages, which collectively define its distinctive architectural character.</p><p>The internal layout was conceived with a high degree of functional clarity: residential family spaces and the architect’s professional office, which also accommodated his interns, are distributed across several levels. A three-room rental apartment was additionally integrated into the programme. A large hall, bedrooms, and ancillary rooms are organised into a coherent and efficient spatial system. The building is crowned by a flat roof terrace, while a landscaped garden with a small fountain was established on the southern side of the plot, reflecting Renaissance spatial concepts.</p><p>The influence of Italian architecture is consistently evident in Kudokas’s work and is particularly pronounced in his own residence. Although the building employs Modernist principles such as free window composition, expansive planar surfaces, and a flat roof, it simultaneously incorporates a rich layer of decorative articulation, including arcaded galleries, ornamental detailing, and sculptural elements. A sculptural work by Bronius Pundzius, Motherhood, is embedded within a niche on the main façade, while a tulip motif bas-relief decorates the tower’s inter-storey zone. This synthesis of functional rationality and ornamental expression is frequently defined as a distinct variant of “Kudokas Modernism”.</p><p>In the interwar period, the villa received official recognition: in 1938 it was awarded a prize by the Kaunas City Municipality for architectural aesthetics and residential comfort. Following the second Soviet occupation in 1944, Kudokas emigrated and continued his professional activity in the United States. His architectural legacy in interwar Lithuania is estimated at approximately 140 realised projects.</p><p>During the Soviet period, the villa was subdivided into multiple apartments and occupied by four households; in the 1980s, its external form was altered through the addition of a pitched roof. Despite these interventions, significant authentic elements have survived, including a wooden staircase with “teraco” steps, parquet flooring, ceiling mouldings, built-in cabinetry, arcaded structures, and balconies.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/43.jpg', '54.89412580', '23.93125010');
