By 1940, the structure, including its 63-metre tower, had been completed, although the interior remained unfinished. In 1941, the building was nationalised by the occupying authorities. The intended house of worship was subsequently repurposed for industrial use: during the German occupation, it functioned as a paper factory, and later it was adapted for a Soviet military-industrial enterprise known as the Radio Factory.</p><p>Characteristic architectural elements, such as the terrace chapel, were dismantled and replaced with auxiliary spaces and technical installations. To accommodate industrial production, the interior was subdivided with reinforced concrete structures: the aisles were divided into three levels and the central nave into five.</p><p>For approximately five decades, the unplastered red-brick structure dominated the Kaunas skyline. It became both a national symbol and a powerful emblem of hope for the restoration of independence. The aspiration to complete the church as a national sanctuary persisted among the population. Following the restoration of independence, reconstruction works were rapidly initiated, symbolising collective renewal and the re-establishment of statehood.</p><p>The façade, articulated by bands of narrow windows, draws the viewer’s gaze and reinforces a sense of verticality and upward movement. As the principal accent of the city panorama, its silhouette bears a resemblance to the stepped profiles of American skyscrapers.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/16.jpg', '54.90264030', '23.91701390');

The former residential section, now arranged as a memorial space, originally comprised three rooms. Despite their modest size, these spaces are associated with a rich historical narrative. A dental practice operated in a room belonging to the artist’s wife, Marija Putvinskaitė, and was reportedly visited by President Antanas Smetona. The daughter’s room contained furniture designed according to her own drawings.

The living room functioned both as a space for daily family meals and as a venue for gatherings of intellectuals. Notably, the house was devoid of curtains, reflecting the guiding principle that one should live transparently, with nothing to conceal.

Antanas Žmuidzinavičius described himself as an avid collector, assembling objects that left a strong personal impression. Among his most distinctive collections is one, comprising nearly 300 horned figures. This collection formed the basis for what later became the world’s only Devils’ Museum. The collection has since been relocated to a new annex, which houses more than 3,000 representations of devils and mythological figures made from diverse materials, including ceramics, wood, leather, and dried organic matter.</p><p>Since 1966, the building has functioned as a branch of the M. K. Čiurlionis National Museum of Art – the Antanas Žmuidzinavičius Creations and Collections Museum.</p>', 'https://modernist.kaunas.lt/ehl-pastatai/20.jpg', '54.90088060', '23.91056480');
1930–1931, architect Antanas Jokimas |3 Aušros St.', 'The present Jono Jablonskio Gymnasium building represents one of the most ambitious and technologically advanced interwar educational projects in Lithuania, reflecting state-driven efforts to establish a modern European system of schooling. Following Lithuania’s independence and the introduction of compulsory primary education in 1922, a substantial demand for new school infrastructure emerged nationwide. In Kaunas alone, 36 primary schools were constructed within a decade, while across Lithuania approximately 80 new educational institutions were built annually from 1932 onwards.', 'Radvilėnų pl. 19', '<p>As the city expanded and the population grew, the Kaunas City Council commissioned engineer and architect Antanas Jokimas to design two modern elementary schools—one for Lithuanian children at the corner of Aušros and Žemaičių Streets, and another for Jewish children near the harbor  (currently Karaliaus Mindaugo Ave.).</p><p>The building on Aušros Street replaced an earlier wooden school operating since 1926 and became the most advanced primary school facility in Lithuania at the time of its completion. Its programme included a gymnasium hall, assembly hall, cinema hall, four handicraft workshops, and the first swimming pool in Lithuania dedicated exclusively to school physical education.</p><p>Upon opening, the institution was named after Jonas Jablonskis and rapidly acquired a reputation as a prestigious educational establishment. Demand for admission was exceptionally high, with pupils from Žaliakalnis and other districts competing for places, resulting in overcrowded classrooms of up to approximately fifty students. Parents consistently emphasised the high academic and disciplinary standards, while the daily schedule was strictly regulated; on Mondays, pupils assembled to pray, sing the Lithuanian national anthem, and listen to the headmaster’s address.</p><p>The architectural design reflects contemporary Modernist principles: extensive glazing ensures natural illumination, ceiling heights are generous, and spatial organisation is based on clear functional zoning. The restrained façades are enlivened by a corner tower element, a fashionable interwar motif, alongside subtle rusticated wall surfaces and minimal decorative articulation.</p><p>During the Second World War, under German occupation, the building was repurposed as a military hospital. In 1946 it was returned to educational use and renamed Primary School No. 10. Subsequently it was reorganised into a seven-year school and later a secondary school; in 1958, the name of Jonas Jablonskis was restored. Over time, two extensions were added, and the institution was elevated to gymnasium status with humanities and science-oriented profiles.</p><p>Over more than eight decades, the Jono Jablonskio Gymnasium has become an important centre for the education of prominent figures in Lithuanian cultural and public life. Among its alumni are President Valdas Adamkus and numerous poets, artists, and political figures, while notable cultural personalities, including composer and carillonneur Viktoras Kuprevičius, were also part of its academic staff.</p>', '../../ehl-pastatai/69e87cf03d939.jpg', '54.90562020', '23.95155250');
